<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT TO DRAFT LAW TO BOOST PUBLISHING INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Jan.  29 (CNA) 01/29/07  19:03:43 (By Y.C. Jou)
</P>
<P>
The government will draft a law in an attempt to boost the
publishing industry, Government Information Office Minister Cheng
Wen-tsang said Monday.
</P>
<P>
He announced the "important goal of the year" at a pre-event news
conference for the Taipei International Book Exhibition 2007,
which will open Tuesday at the Taipei World Trade Center halls
and run through Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
Cheng said the bill will contain measures to support book,
magazine, newspaper and audio and digital publishing to promote
diversification in the industry.
</P>
<P>
The annual book fair is being held for the 15th year and this
year features Russian culture. Five Russian authors -- Sergey
Lukyanenko, Eduard Uspensky, Andrey Bitov, Yuri Poliakov and
Victor Erofeev -- will be present at the event. The fair will
also show "The Stroll" directed by Alexey Uchitel, as the opening
film at the festival,  according to a spokesman for the Taipei
Book Fair Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Hao Ming-yi, chairman of the foundation, said Southeast Asia will
also be one of the themes of the event.
</P>
